### Introduction
I personally find it much easier to think of a top-down memoization approach first before tackling a DP solution. As such, I'll try my best to demonstrate how one might make the transition from top-down to bottom-up. Before that, let's make sure we're on the same page regarding the top-down approach.

Just to make it clear why the left and right cells are chosen using `i` and `i+1`, I've illustrated the logic below:
![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/6fbb6fbb-3f8a-4ba0-9f99-b78247b66791_1655082032.7091029.png)

___
### Top-Down Memoization Approach:
The easiest way to implement this is through recursion. It's quite simply DFS; from the current cell, find the minimum path between the left cell and the right cell. 
We simply start from the root cell (i.e. the top of the triangle) and work our way down. The results of each individual cell will bubble all the way up to our root and we can simply return that answer. I've written the code for this approach below. The fundamental logic for the recursive call is this:
```java
int path = triangle.get(level).get(index); // get the current value
if (level < triangle.size() - 1) 
	path += Math.min(dfs(level + 1, index, triangle), dfs(level + 1, index + 1, triangle)); // add that to the minimum path
```
 <ins>This will be the key to converting from top-down to bottom-up</ins>.

To address the memoization aspect of this approach: 
Since we're doing a lot of repetitive work, we would like to cache our results at each cell in a memo table to avoid recomputing the shortest path for a particular cell. This is possible since the shortest path from any cell in the triangle is *always* going to be the same.

___
### Bottom-Up DP Approach:
It can sometimes be tricky knowing how to convert to a DP solution. However, I'll try to make it as clear as possible. We can essentially boil down the conversion to the following steps:
1. Identify where our top-down approach starts and ends. Then, flip them around in our DP approach.
	* In this question, we start at the top level of the triangle and end at the bottom level. We'll do it the other way around for DP.

2. Convert from recursive calls to a for-loop. 
	* In this question, each call represents a different level and at each level we look at different indices (cells) on that same level.
	* This is basically just two for loops: one looping through each level, and another looping through each cell of that level.

3. Observe how the top-down approach collects information from the *next* recursive call.
	* In this question, as aforementioned, we get the <ins>current cell value + the minimum path between the left and right cells on the next level</ins>.
	* This is identical to how we do it in DP: `dp[level][i] = triangle.get(level).get(i) + Math.min(dp[level+1][i], dp[level+1][i+1]);`

The most important step here is step 3. Another way to think about it is transfering what's stored in the memo table into the dp table. If it doesn't quite make sense yet, have a look at the two approaches in code below and note down as many similarities as you can. Hope this helps! 

![image](https://assets.leetcode.com/users/images/3e826562-baec-4b76-8757-0d9b31fdbead_1655084237.4187193.png)

___
### Code:
If you have any questions, suggestions or improvements, feel free to let me know. Thanks for reading!

**Top-Down Memoization:**
> Time complexity: `O(n^2)`
> Space complexity: `O(n^2)` 
```java
private Integer[][] memo;

public int minimumTotal(List<List<Integer>> triangle) {
	int n = triangle.size();
	memo = new Integer[n][n];
	return dfs(0, 0, triangle);
}

private int dfs(int level, int i, List<List<Integer>> triangle) {
	if (memo[level][i] != null) return memo[level][i];

	int path = triangle.get(level).get(i);
	if (level < triangle.size() - 1) 
		path += Math.min(dfs(level + 1, i, triangle), dfs(level + 1, i + 1, triangle));

	return memo[level][i] = path;
}
```

**Bottom-Up DP:**
> Time Complexity: `O(n^2)`
> Space Complexity: `O(n^2)`
```java
public int minimumTotal(List<List<Integer>> triangle) {
	int n = triangle.size();
	int[][] dp = new int[n+1][n+1];

	for (int level=n-1; level>=0; level--)
		for (int i=0; i<=level; i++)
			dp[level][i] = triangle.get(level).get(i) + Math.min(dp[level+1][i], dp[level+1][i+1]);

	return dp[0][0];
}
```
(We can make our DP solution `O(n)` space by only storing the level immediately above the current one since we don't need to store the whole thing).

