solutions.content:
So, the idea is to move down our triangle like we would navigate in a graph with a BFS approach, layer by layer - but instead of preparing each layer as a series of new branches and leafs, we just cumulate the minimum possible path.

So, given the example:

```
[
     [2],
    [3,4],
   [6,5,7],
  [4,1,8,3]
]
```

We proceed with the first step and recompute the second row with with the (minimum) overall cost of getting there:

```
[
     [2],
    [5,6], // 3 + 2, 4 + 2
   [6,5,7],
  [4,1,8,3]
]
```

Then comes the third layer and notice that things start to get interesting, since the central value (`5`) has 2 possible ancestors, but we only keep the smaller one - the `5` in the second row:

```
[
     [2],
    [5,6],
   [11,10,13], // 6 + 5, 5 + 5, 7 + 6
  [4,1,8,3]
]
```

Finally, last round:

```
[
     [2],
    [5,6],
   [11,10,13],
  [15,11,18,16] // 4 + 11, 1 + 10, 8 + 10, 3 + 13
]
```

Last step, we get the minimum value from the last row: `11`.

The code below describes this approach (see the comments for the details), moving from each row starting from the second up to the end and noticing that the first and last elements of each row only have an ancestor (the matching extreme of the previous row), while all the others instead pick the minimum of their 2 possible parents:

```cpp
class Solution {
public:
    int minimumTotal(vector<vector<int>>& triangle) {
        int len = triangle.size(), rowLen;
        // parsing all the rows after the first
        for (int i = 1; i < len; i++) {
            rowLen = triangle[i].size();
            // looping through each row elements, incrementing it with
            // the minimum direct ancestor
            for (int j = 0; j < rowLen; j++) {
                // case for the first element of a row
                if (!j) triangle[i][j] += triangle[i - 1][0];
                // case for the last element of a row
                else if (j == rowLen - 1) triangle[i][j] += triangle[i - 1][j - 1];
                // all the others
                else triangle[i][j] += min(triangle[i - 1][j - 1], triangle[i - 1][j]);
            }
        }
        // finally, we return the minimum cumulated value in the very last row
        return accumulate(begin(triangle[len - 1]), end(triangle[len - 1]), INT_MAX, [](int a, int b){return min(a, b);});
    }
};
```

And after about one year, I came up with an even more performing solution:

```cpp
class Solution {
public:
    int minimumTotal(vector<vector<int>>& triangle) {
        // computing the min path in place
        for (int i = 1, lmt = triangle.size(); i < lmt; i++) {
            auto prevRow = triangle[i - 1], &currRow = triangle[i];
            // updating the first item
            currRow.front() += prevRow.front();
            // updating mid elements
            for (int j = 1, lmtRow = prevRow.size(); j < lmtRow; j++) currRow[j] += min(prevRow[j - 1], prevRow[j]);
            // updating the last item
            currRow.back() += prevRow.back();
        }
        return *min_element(begin(triangle.back()), end(triangle.back()));
    }
};
```

